title: Basic Usage
text: {logitr} package requires data structured data.frame arranged “long” format [@Wickham2014] row contains data single alternative choice observation. choice observations symmetric, meaning can “ragged” structure different choice observations different numbers alternatives. data must also include variables following: Outcome: dummy-coded variable identifies alternative chosen (1 chosen, 0 chosen). one alternative 1 per choice observation. Observation ID: sequence repeated numbers identifies unique choice observation. example, first three choice observations 2 alternatives , first 6 rows obsID variable 1, 1, 2, 2, 3, 3. Covariates: variables used model covariates. “Data Formatting Encoding” vignette details required data format.

title: Basic Usage
text: Models specified estimated using logitr() function. data argument set data frame containing data, outcome obsID arguments set column names data frame correspond dummy-coded outcome (choice) variable observation ID variable, respectively. variables used model covariates provided vector column names pars argument. variable vector additively included covariate utility model, interpretation represent utilities preference space models WTPs WTP space model. example, consider preference space model utility yogurt given following utility model: uj=αpj+β1xj1+β2xj2+β3xj3+β4xj4+εj,\begin{equation}     u_{j} =         \alpha p_{j} +         \beta_1 x_{j1} +         \beta_2 x_{j2} +         \beta_3 x_{j3} +         \beta_4 x_{j4} +         \varepsilon_{j}, \label{eq:yogurtUtilityPref} \end{equation} pjp_{j} price, xj1x_{j1} feat, xj2−4x_{j2-4} dummy-coded variables brand (fourth brand representing reference level). model can estimated using logitr() function follows: equivalent model WTP space given following utility model: uj=λ(ω1xj1+ω1xj2+ω1xj3+ω2xj4−pj)+εj,\begin{equation}     u_{j} =         \lambda \left(             \omega_1 x_{j1} +             \omega_1 x_{j2} +             \omega_1 x_{j3} +             \omega_2 x_{j4} -             p_{j}         \right) +         \varepsilon_{j}, \label{eq:yogurtUtilityWtp} \end{equation} specify model, simply move "price" pars argument scalePar argument: model, variables pars marginal WTPs, whereas preference space model marginal utilities. Price separately specified scalePar argument acts scaling term WTP space models. price typical scaling variable, continuous variables can also used, time. Interactions covariates can entered pars vector separated * symbol. example, interaction price feat preference space model included specifying pars = c("price", "feat", "brand", "price*feat"), even concisely just pars = c("price*feat", "brand") interaction price feat produce individual parameters price feat addition interaction parameter. examples multinomial logit models fixed parameters. See “Estimating Multinomial Logit Models” vignette details.
code: library("logitr")  mnl_pref <- logitr(     data    = yogurt,     outcome = "choice",     obsID   = "obsID",     pars    = c("price", "feat", "brand") ) mnl_wtp <- logitr(     data     = yogurt,     outcome  = "choice",     obsID    = "obsID",     pars     = c("feat", "brand"),     scalePar = "price" )

title: Basic Usage
text: Since WTP space models non-linear non-convex log-likelihood functions, recommended use multi-start search run optimization loop multiple times search different local minima. implemented using numMultiStarts argument, e.g.: multi-start parallelized default faster estimation, number cores use can manually set using numCores argument. numCores provide, number cores set parallel::detectCores() - 1. models larger data sets, may need set numCores = 1 avoid memory overflow issues.
code: mnl_wtp <- logitr(     data     = yogurt,     outcome  = "choice",     obsID    = "obsID",     pars     = c("feat", "brand"),     scalePar = "price",     numMultiStarts = 10 )

title: Basic Usage
text: See “Estimating Mixed Logit Models” vignette details. estimate mixed logit model, use randPars argument logitr() function denote parameters modeled distribution. current package version supports normal ("n"), log-normal ("ln"), zero-censored normal ("cn") distributions. example, assume observed utility yogurts vj=αpj+β1xj1+β2xj2+β3xj3+β4xj4v_{j} = \alpha p_{j} + \beta_1 x_{j1} + \beta_2 x_{j2} + \beta_3 x_{j3} + \beta_4 x_{j4}, pjp_{j} price, xj1x_{j1} feat, xj2−4x_{j2-4} dummy-coded variables brand. model feat well brands normally-distributed, set randPars = c(feat = "n", brand = "n"): Since mixed logit models also non-convex log-likelihood functions, recommended use multi-start search run optimization loop multiple times search different local minima.
code: mxl_pref <- logitr(     data     = yogurt,     outcome  = 'choice',     obsID    = 'obsID',     pars     = c('price', 'feat', 'brand'),     randPars = c(feat = 'n', brand = 'n'),     numMultiStarts = 10 )

title: Basic Usage
text: Estimated models can used predict probabilities outcomes set (multiple sets) alternatives based estimated model. example, consider predicting probabilities two choice observations yogurt dataset: example , probabilities two sets alternatives computed using fixed parameter mnl_pref model using predict() method: resulting probs data frame contains expected probabilities alternative. lower upper predictions reflect 95% confidence interval (controlled ci argument), estimated using Krinsky Robb parametric bootstrapping method [@Krinsky1986]. default ci = NULL, case CI predictions made. WTP space models can also used predict probabilities: can also use predict() method predict outcomes setting type = "outcome" (default value "prob" predicting probabilities). new data provided newdata, outcomes predicted every alternative original data used estimate model. example returnData argument also set TRUE predicted outcomes can compared actual ones. can quickly compute accuracy dividing number correctly predicted choices total number choices: See “Predicting Probabilities Choices Estimated Models” vignette details making predictions.

title: Benchmarking estimation speed against other packages
text: {logitr} package includes runtimes data frame exported Google Colab notebook used conduct benchmark. tables summarize run times package many times slower relative {logitr}. code plots relative run times Colab notebook.
code: library(logitr) library(dplyr) library(tidyr) library(kableExtra) # For tables  numDraws <- unique(runtimes$numDraws) logitr_time <- runtimes %>%     filter(package == "logitr") %>%     rename(time_logitr = time_sec) time_compare <- runtimes %>%     left_join(select(logitr_time, -package), by = "numDraws") %>%     mutate(mult = round(time_sec/ time_logitr, 1)) %>%     select(-time_logitr) # Compare raw times time_compare %>%     select(-mult) %>%     pivot_wider(names_from = numDraws, values_from = time_sec) %>%      kbl() # Compare how many times slower compared to logitr time_compare %>%     select(-time_sec) %>%     pivot_wider(names_from = numDraws, values_from = mult) %>%      kbl() library(ggplot2) library(ggrepel)  plotColors <- c("black", RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(n = 5, name = "Set1"), "gold") benchmark <- runtimes %>%      ggplot(aes(x = numDraws, y = time_sec, color = package)) +     geom_line() +     geom_point() +     geom_text_repel(         data = . %>% filter(numDraws == max(numDraws)),         aes(label = package),         hjust = 0, nudge_x = 40, direction = "y",         size = 4.5, segment.size = 0     ) +     scale_x_continuous(         limits = c(0, 1200),         breaks = numDraws,         labels = scales::comma) +     scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 300), breaks = seq(0, 300, 100)) +     scale_color_manual(values = plotColors) +     guides(         point = guide_legend(override.aes = list(label = "")),         color = guide_legend(override.aes = list(label = ""))) +     theme_bw(base_size = 18) +     theme(         panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),         panel.grid.major.x = element_blank(),         legend.position = "none",         axis.line.x = element_blank(),         axis.ticks.x = element_blank()     ) +     labs(         x = "Number of random draws",         y = "Computation time (seconds)"     )  benchmark

title: WTP space convergence issues in other packages
text: Format yogurt data “wide” format {apollo} Define {apollo} probabilities function Define random parameters function Main control settings {apollo}
code: yogurt_price <- yogurt %>%     select(id, obsID, price, brand) %>%     mutate(price = -1*price) %>%     pivot_wider(         names_from  = 'brand',         values_from = 'price') %>%     rename(         price_dannon  = dannon,         price_hiland  = hiland,         price_weight  = weight,         price_yoplait = yoplait) yogurt_feat <- yogurt %>%     select(id, obsID, feat, brand) %>%     pivot_wider(         names_from = 'brand',         values_from = 'feat') %>%     rename(         feat_dannon  = dannon,         feat_hiland  = hiland,         feat_weight  = weight,         feat_yoplait = yoplait) yogurt_choice <- yogurt %>%     filter(choice == 1) %>%     select(id, obsID, choice = alt) data_apollo <- yogurt_price %>%     left_join(yogurt_feat, by = c('id', 'obsID')) %>%     left_join(yogurt_choice, by = c('id', 'obsID')) %>%     arrange(id, obsID) %>%     mutate(       av_dannon  = 1,       av_hiland  = 1,       av_weight  = 1,       av_yoplait = 1     ) apollo_probabilities_wtp <- function(   apollo_beta, apollo_inputs, functionality = "estimate" ) {      ### Attach inputs and detach after function exit     apollo_attach(apollo_beta, apollo_inputs)     on.exit(apollo_detach(apollo_beta, apollo_inputs))      ### Create list of probabilities P     P <- list()      ### List of utilities: these must use the same names as in mnl_settings,     #   order is irrelevant     V <- list()     V[["dannon"]] <- scalePar * (b_feat * feat_dannon - price_dannon)     V[["hiland"]] <- scalePar * (b_brandhiland + b_feat * feat_hiland - price_hiland)     V[["weight"]] <- scalePar * (b_brandweight + b_feat * feat_weight - price_weight)     V[["yoplait"]] <- scalePar * (b_brandyoplait + b_feat * feat_yoplait - price_yoplait)      ### Define settings for MNL model component     mnl_settings <- list(         alternatives = c(dannon = 1, hiland = 2, weight = 3, yoplait = 4),         avail = list(           dannon = av_dannon,           hiland = av_hiland,           weight = av_weight,           yoplait = av_yoplait),         choiceVar = choice,         utilities = V     )      ### Compute probabilities using MNL model     P[["model"]] <- apollo_mnl(mnl_settings, functionality)     ### Take product across observation for same individual     P <- apollo_panelProd(P, apollo_inputs, functionality)     ### Average across inter-individual draws     P = apollo_avgInterDraws(P, apollo_inputs, functionality)     ### Prepare and return outputs of function     P <- apollo_prepareProb(P, apollo_inputs, functionality)      return(P) } apollo_randCoeff <- function(apollo_beta, apollo_inputs) {     randcoeff <- list()     randcoeff[['b_feat']] <- feat + d_feat * sd_feat     randcoeff[['b_brandhiland']] <- brandhiland + d_brandhiland * sd_brandhiland     randcoeff[['b_brandweight']] <- brandweight + d_brandweight * sd_brandweight     randcoeff[['b_brandyoplait']] <- brandyoplait + d_brandyoplait * sd_brandyoplait     return(randcoeff) } apollo_control_wtp <- list(     modelName       = "MXL_WTP_space",     modelDescr      = "MXL model on yogurt choice SP data, in WTP space",     indivID         = "id",     mixing          = TRUE,     analyticGrad    = TRUE,     panelData       = TRUE,     nCores          = 1 )  # Set parameters for generating draws apollo_draws_n <- list(     interDrawsType = "halton",     interNDraws    = numDraws_wtp,     interUnifDraws = c(),     interNormDraws = c(         "d_feat", "d_brandhiland", "d_brandweight", "d_brandyoplait"),     intraDrawsType = "halton",     intraNDraws    = 0,     intraUnifDraws = c(),     intraNormDraws = c() )  # Set input apollo_inputs_wtp <- apollo_validateInputs(     apollo_beta      = start_wtp,     apollo_fixed     = NULL,     database         = data_apollo,     apollo_draws     = apollo_draws_n,     apollo_randCoeff = apollo_randCoeff,     apollo_control   = apollo_control_wtp )

title: WTP space convergence issues in other packages
text: Format yogurt data “wide” format {mixl} Define {mixl} utility function
code: data_mixl <- data_apollo # Uses the same "wide" format as {apollo} data_mixl$ID <- data_mixl$id data_mixl$CHOICE <- data_mixl$choice mixl_wtp <- "     feat_RND = @feat + draw_1 * @sd_feat;     brandhiland_RND = @brandhiland + draw_2 * @sd_brandhiland;     brandweight_RND = @brandweight + draw_3 * @sd_brandweight;     brandyoplait_RND = @brandyoplait + draw_4 * @sd_brandyoplait;     U_1 = @scalePar * (feat_RND * $feat_dannon - $price_dannon);     U_2 = @scalePar * (brandhiland_RND + feat_RND * $feat_hiland - $price_hiland);     U_3 = @scalePar * (brandweight_RND + feat_RND * $feat_weight - $price_weight);     U_4 = @scalePar * (brandyoplait_RND + feat_RND * $feat_yoplait - $price_yoplait); " mixl_spec_wtp <- specify_model(mixl_wtp, data_mixl) availabilities <- generate_default_availabilities(data_mixl, 4)

title: WTP space convergence issues in other packages
text: First attempt using starting points {logitr} {mixl} converges local minimum: Second attempt using {logitr} solution starting points , {mixl} converges local minimum (though ’s closer previous solution):
code: model_mixl <- estimate(     mixl_spec_wtp, start_wtp,     data_mixl, availabilities,     nDraws = numDraws_wtp ) c(logLik(model_logitr), logLik(model_mixl)) #> [1]  -718.0862 -1544.8531 cbind(coef(model_logitr), coef(model_mixl)) #>                        [,1]        [,2] #> scalePar          0.3789865 -2270.55731 #> feat              1.7468317    42.24281 #> brandhiland     -13.7087157    24.36731 #> brandweight      -9.3828735   110.99687 #> brandyoplait      4.2515734  -492.36959 #> sd_feat          -0.9308170    10.81470 #> sd_brandhiland   -4.8418491    10.23414 #> sd_brandweight   10.8495725   334.92761 #> sd_brandyoplait   7.8130522   915.14924 model_mixl <- estimate(     mixl_spec_wtp, coef(model_logitr),     data_mixl, availabilities,     nDraws = numDraws_wtp ) c(logLik(model_logitr), logLik(model_mixl)) #> [1] -718.0862 -761.5228 cbind(coef(model_logitr), coef(model_mixl)) #>                        [,1]          [,2] #> scalePar          0.3789865    0.01959803 #> feat              1.7468317   66.46247619 #> brandhiland     -13.7087157 -172.32720627 #> brandweight      -9.3828735 -114.92946558 #> brandyoplait      4.2515734    6.24519288 #> sd_feat          -0.9308170  -36.14686337 #> sd_brandhiland   -4.8418491 -227.05348964 #> sd_brandweight   10.8495725  198.52035799 #> sd_brandyoplait   7.8130522  173.44727278

title: WTP space convergence issues in other packages
text: First attempt using starting points {logitr}. Note additional starting parameters must added {gmnl} approach estimating WTP slightly different model. {gmnl} converges local minimum: Second attempt using {logitr} solution starting points: , {gmnl} converges local minimum:
code: model_gmnl <- gmnl(     data = data_gmnl,     formula = choice ~ price + feat + brand | 0 | 0 | 0 | 1,     ranp = c(         feat = "n", brandhiland = "n", brandweight = "n",         brandyoplait = "n"),     fixed = c(TRUE, rep(FALSE, 10), TRUE),     model = "gmnl",     method = "bfgs",     haltons = NA,     panel = TRUE,     start = c(start_wtp, 0.1, 0.1, 0),     R = numDraws_wtp ) c(logLik(model_logitr), logLik(model_gmnl)) #> [1]  -718.0862 -1710.6872 cbind(coef(model_logitr), coef(model_gmnl)) #>                        [,1]         [,2] #> feat              0.3789865    8.1540692 #> brandhiland       1.7468317    4.4266391 #> brandweight     -13.7087157   20.9581382 #> brandyoplait     -9.3828735  -93.0969112 #> het.(Intercept)   4.2515734 -440.5183170 #> sd.feat          -0.9308170    2.4208585 #> sd.brandhiland   -4.8418491    0.1085233 #> sd.brandweight   10.8495725   53.2376327 #> sd.brandyoplait   7.8130522   95.0008933 #> tau               0.3789865  653.9956379 model_gmnl <- gmnl(     data = data_gmnl,     formula = choice ~ price + feat + brand | 0 | 0 | 0 | 1,     ranp = c(         feat = "n", brandhiland = "n", brandweight = "n",         brandyoplait = "n"),     fixed = c(TRUE, rep(FALSE, 10), TRUE),     model = "gmnl",     method = "bfgs",     haltons = NA,     panel = TRUE,     start = c(coef(model_logitr), 0.1, 0.1, 0),     R = numDraws_wtp ) c(logLik(model_logitr), logLik(model_gmnl)) #> [1] -718.0862 -944.3339 cbind(coef(model_logitr), coef(model_gmnl)) #>                        [,1]       [,2] #> feat              0.3789865   2.321317 #> brandhiland       1.7468317 -18.785933 #> brandweight     -13.7087157  -5.977394 #> brandyoplait     -9.3828735   1.761744 #> het.(Intercept)   4.2515734   6.168432 #> sd.feat          -0.9308170   2.830422 #> sd.brandhiland   -4.8418491   6.358857 #> sd.brandweight   10.8495725  10.600978 #> sd.brandyoplait   7.8130522   5.455189 #> tau               0.3789865   8.230516

title: WTP space convergence issues in other packages
text: First attempt using starting points {logitr}: {apollo} fails converge just returns starting coefficients: Second attempt using {logitr} solution starting points: time {apollo} converges local minimum:
code: model_apollo <- apollo_estimate(     apollo_beta          = start_wtp,     apollo_fixed         = NULL,     apollo_probabilities = apollo_probabilities_wtp,     apollo_inputs        = apollo_inputs_wtp,     estimate_settings    = list(printLevel = 0) ) c(logLik(model_logitr), model_apollo$LLout) #>                 model  #>  -718.0862 -2928.4048 cbind(coef(model_logitr), coef(model_apollo)) #>                        [,1] #> scalePar          0.3789865 #> feat              1.7468317 #> brandhiland     -13.7087157 #> brandweight      -9.3828735 #> brandyoplait      4.2515734 #> sd_feat          -0.9308170 #> sd_brandhiland   -4.8418491 #> sd_brandweight   10.8495725 #> sd_brandyoplait   7.8130522 model_apollo <- apollo_estimate(     apollo_beta          = coef(model_logitr),     apollo_fixed         = NULL,     apollo_probabilities = apollo_probabilities_wtp,     apollo_inputs        = apollo_inputs_wtp,     estimate_settings    = list(printLevel = 0) ) c(logLik(model_logitr), model_apollo$LLout) #>               model  #> -718.0862 -769.7493 cbind(coef(model_logitr), model_apollo$betaStop) #>                        [,1]          [,2] #> scalePar          0.3789865  2.376434e-04 #> feat              1.7468317  5.213661e+03 #> brandhiland     -13.7087157 -1.622643e+04 #> brandweight      -9.3828735 -1.529634e+04 #> brandyoplait      4.2515734  4.573893e+03 #> sd_feat          -0.9308170  6.131294e+02 #> sd_brandhiland   -4.8418491 -9.461200e+03 #> sd_brandweight   10.8495725  1.260092e+04 #> sd_brandyoplait   7.8130522  1.347027e+04

title: Data Formatting and Encoding
text: {logitr} package requires data structured data.frame arranged “long” format [@Wickham2014] row contains data single alternative choice observation. choice observations symmetric, meaning can “ragged” structure different choice observations different numbers alternatives. data must also include variables following: Outcome: dummy-coded variable identifies alternative chosen (1 chosen, 0 chosen). one alternative 1 per choice observation. Observation ID: sequence repeated numbers identifies unique choice observation. example, first three choice observations 2 alternatives , first 6 rows obsID variable 1, 1, 2, 2, 3, 3. Covariates: variables used model covariates. {logitr} package contains several example data sets illustrate data structure. example, yogurt contains observations yogurt purchases panel 100 households [@Jain1994]. Choice identified choice column, observation ID identified obsID column, columns price, feat, brand can used model covariates: data set also includes alt variable determines alternatives included choice set observation id variable determines individual data panel structure containing multiple choice observations individual.
code: library("logitr")  head(yogurt) #>   id obsID alt choice price feat   brand #> 1  1     1   1      0   8.1    0  dannon #> 2  1     1   2      0   6.1    0  hiland #> 3  1     1   3      1   7.9    0  weight #> 4  1     1   4      0  10.8    0 yoplait #> 5  1     2   1      1   9.8    0  dannon #> 6  1     2   2      0   6.4    0  hiland

title: Data Formatting and Encoding
text: Variables modeled either continuous discrete based data type. Numeric variables default estimated single “slope” coefficient. example, consider data frame contains price variable levels $10, $15, $20. Adding price pars argument main logitr() function result single price coefficient “slope” change price. contrast, categorical variables (.e. character factor type variables) default estimated coefficient first level, serves reference level. default reference level determined alphabetically, can also set modifying factor levels variable. example, default reference level brand variable "dannon" alphabetically first. set "weight" reference level, factor levels can modified using factor() function:
code: yogurt2 <- yogurt  brands <- c("weight", "hiland", "yoplait", "dannon") yogurt2$brand <- factor(yogurt2$brand, levels = brands)

title: Data Formatting and Encoding
text: wish make dummy-coded variables use model, recommend using dummy_cols() function {fastDummies} package. example, code , create dummy-coded columns brand variable use variables covariates model: yogurt2 data frame now new dummy-coded columns brand: Now can use columns covariates:
code: yogurt2 <- fastDummies::dummy_cols(yogurt2, "brand") head(yogurt2) #> # A tibble: 6 × 11 #>      id obsID   alt choice price  feat brand   brand_weight brand_hiland #>   <dbl> <int> <int>  <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <fct>          <int>        <int> #> 1     1     1     1      0  8.1      0 dannon             0            0 #> 2     1     1     2      0  6.10     0 hiland             0            1 #> 3     1     1     3      1  7.90     0 weight             1            0 #> 4     1     1     4      0 10.8      0 yoplait            0            0 #> 5     1     2     1      1  9.80     0 dannon             0            0 #> 6     1     2     2      0  6.40     0 hiland             0            1 #> # ℹ 2 more variables: brand_yoplait <int>, brand_dannon <int> mnl_pref_dummies <- logitr(   data    = yogurt2,   outcome = 'choice',   obsID   = 'obsID',   pars    = c(     'price', 'feat', 'brand_yoplait', 'brand_dannon', 'brand_weight'   ) )  summary(mnl_pref_dummies) #> ================================================= #>  #> Model estimated on: Fri Dec 19 21:44:05 2025  #>  #> Using logitr version: 1.1.3  #>  #> Call: #> logitr(data = yogurt2, outcome = "choice", obsID = "obsID", pars = c("price",  #>     "feat", "brand_yoplait", "brand_dannon", "brand_weight")) #>  #> Frequencies of alternatives: #>        1        2        3        4  #> 0.402156 0.029436 0.229270 0.339138  #>  #> Exit Status: 3, Optimization stopped because ftol_rel or ftol_abs was reached. #>                                  #> Model Type:    Multinomial Logit #> Model Space:          Preference #> Model Run:                1 of 1 #> Iterations:                   18 #> Elapsed Time:        0h:0m:0.03s #> Algorithm:        NLOPT_LD_LBFGS #> Weights Used?:             FALSE #> Robust? title: Data Formatting and Encoding
text: estimating model, often helpful validate data properly formatted. validate_data() function checks common formatting errors provides detailed diagnostic information. can save time catching errors attempt estimate model.

title: Data Formatting and Encoding
text: minimum, validate outcome obsID columns: function returns validation object indicates whether data valid provides summary information data structure.
code: validation <- validate_data(   data = yogurt,   outcome = "choice",   obsID = "obsID" )  validation #> === LOGITR DATA VALIDATION === #>  #> Data Overview: #>   Rows: 9648  #>   Columns: 7  #>   Outcome variable: choice  #>   Observation ID: obsID  #>  #> Data Structure: #>   Total observations: 2412  #>   Total alternatives: 9648  #>   Valid choices: 2412  #>   Alternatives per observation: #>      4 alternatives: 2412 observations #>  #> === VALIDATION RESULTS === #> ✓ Data validation PASSED - no issues found! #> ✓ Data appears ready for use with logitr()!

text: can also validate specific parameters check missing values issues:
code: validation <- validate_data(   data = yogurt,   outcome = "choice",   obsID = "obsID",   pars = c("price", "feat", "brand") )  validation #> === LOGITR DATA VALIDATION === #>  #> Data Overview: #>   Rows: 9648  #>   Columns: 7  #>   Outcome variable: choice  #>   Observation ID: obsID  #>   Parameters: price, feat, brand  #>  #> Data Structure: #>   Total observations: 2412  #>   Total alternatives: 9648  #>   Valid choices: 2412  #>   Alternatives per observation: #>      4 alternatives: 2412 observations #>  #> Parameter Information: #>    price ( numeric ): range [ 0.3 , 19.3 ] #>    feat ( numeric ): range [ 0 , 1 ] #>    brand ( character ):  4 levels - dannon, hiland, weight, yoplait #>  #> === VALIDATION RESULTS === #> ✓ Data validation PASSED - no issues found! #> ✓ Data appears ready for use with logitr()!

text: panel data, can validate panel structure:
code: validation <- validate_data(   data = yogurt,   outcome = "choice",   obsID = "obsID",   pars = c("price", "feat", "brand"),   panelID = "id" )  validation #> === LOGITR DATA VALIDATION === #>  #> Data Overview: #>   Rows: 9648  #>   Columns: 7  #>   Outcome variable: choice  #>   Observation ID: obsID  #>   Parameters: price, feat, brand  #>   Panel ID: id  #>  #> Data Structure: #>   Total observations: 2412  #>   Total alternatives: 9648  #>   Valid choices: 2412  #>   Alternatives per observation: #>      4 alternatives: 2412 observations #>   Panel structure: #>     Individuals: 100  #>     Observations per individual: Min = 4 , Max = 185 , Mean = 24.1  #>  #> Parameter Information: #>    price ( numeric ): range [ 0.3 , 19.3 ] #>    feat ( numeric ): range [ 0 , 1 ] #>    brand ( character ):  4 levels - dannon, hiland, weight, yoplait #>  #> === VALIDATION RESULTS === #> ✓ Data validation PASSED - no issues found! #> ✓ Data appears ready for use with logitr()!

title: Data Formatting and Encoding
text: validate_data() function checks several common formatting errors: Multiple choices per observation: obsID exactly one choice (outcome = 1) choice observation: obsID must least one choice Non-contiguous observation blocks: rows obsID must grouped together Invalid outcome values: outcome variable must contain 0 1 (TRUE FALSE) Missing values: Checks missing values required columns ’s example detecting error:
code: # Create problematic data with multiple choices in one observation bad_data <- yogurt bad_data$choice[1:2] <- 1  validation <- validate_data(   data = bad_data,   outcome = "choice",   obsID = "obsID" )  validation #> === LOGITR DATA VALIDATION === #>  #> Data Overview: #>   Rows: 9648  #>   Columns: 7  #>   Outcome variable: choice  #>   Observation ID: obsID  #>  #> Data Structure: #>   Total observations: 2412  #>   Total alternatives: 9648  #>   Valid choices: 2411  #>   Alternatives per observation: #>      4 alternatives: 2412 observations #>  #> === VALIDATION RESULTS === #> ✗ ERRORS found: #>    1 . Multiple choices (>1) found in obsID(s): 1   #>  #>   Detailed locations for multiple choices: #>     ObsID 1 - rows: 1, 2, 3, 4  #>  #>  Please fix the errors above before using with logitr().

title: Estimating Models with Interactions
text: add interactions covariates model, can add additional arguments pars vector logitr() function separated * symbol. example, let’s say want interact price feat following model: , add "price*feat" pars vector: model now estimated coefficient price*feat effect:

text: want include interactions individual-specific variables (example, assess difference effect groups respondents), include individual-specific variable interactions using * pars. interactions inside pars automatically generate interaction coefficient well coefficients covariate. example, group variable determined whether individuals belongs group group B, including price*group pars create coefficients price, groupA, price:groupA, groupA coefficient unidentified. case, include price price:groupA model. now, way handle situation manually create dummy-coded interaction variables include model. illustrate one might , consider yogurt data frame two groups individuals: B. simple illustration, ’ll define groups arbitrarily based whether obsID even odd: interaction group variable price can included model first manually creating price_groupA interaction variable including pars: model now attribute coefficients price, feat, brand well interaction group price:

title: Estimating Multinomial Logit Models
text: example estimate following homogeneous multinomial logit model preference space: uj=αpj+β1xjFeat+β2xjHiland+β3xjWeight+β4xjYoplait+εj\begin{equation}     u_{j} =         \alpha p_{j} +         \beta_1 x_{j}^{\mathrm{Feat}} +         \beta_2 x_{j}^{\mathrm{Hiland}} +         \beta_3 x_{j}^{\mathrm{Weight}} +         \beta_4 x_{j}^{\mathrm{Yoplait}}  +         \varepsilon_{j} \label{eq:mnlPrefExample} \end{equation} parameters α\alpha, β1\beta_1, β2\beta_2, β3\beta_3, β4\beta_4 units utility. text: example estimate following homogeneous multinomial logit model WTP space: uj=λ(ω1xjFeat+ω2xjHiland+ω3xjWeight+ω4xjYoplait−pj)+εj\begin{equation}     u_{j} =         \lambda (         \omega_1 x_{j}^{\mathrm{Feat}} +         \omega_2 x_{j}^{\mathrm{Hiland}} +         \omega_3 x_{j}^{\mathrm{Weight}} +         \omega_4 x_{j}^{\mathrm{Yoplait}} -         p_{j})  +         \varepsilon_{j} \label{eq:mnlWtpExample} \end{equation} parameters ω1\omega_1, ω2\omega_2, ω3\omega_3, ω4\omega_4 units dollars λ\lambda scale parameter. title: Estimating Weighted Logit Models
text: example, ’ll estimate two versions following utility model WTP space: one without weights one weights. Notation taken Helveston et al. (2015): uj=λ(ω1xjhev+ω2xjphev10+ω3xjphev20+ω4xjphev40+ω5xjbev75+ω6xjbev100+ω7xjbev150+ω8xjphevFastcharge+ω9xjbevFastcharge+ω10xjopCost+ω11xjaccelTime+ω12xjamerican+ω13xjjapanese+ω14xjchinese+ω15xjskorean−pj)+εj\begin{equation} \begin{split} &u_{j} = \lambda (\\ &\omega_1 x_{j}^{\mathrm{hev}} +  \omega_2 x_{j}^{\mathrm{phev10}} +  \omega_3 x_{j}^{\mathrm{phev20}} +  \omega_4 x_{j}^{\mathrm{phev40}} +\\ &\omega_5 x_{j}^{\mathrm{bev75}} +  \omega_6 x_{j}^{\mathrm{bev100}} +  \omega_7 x_{j}^{\mathrm{bev150}} +\\ &\omega_8 x_{j}^{\mathrm{phevFastcharge}} +  \omega_9 x_{j}^{\mathrm{bevFastcharge}} +  \omega_{10} x_{j}^{\mathrm{opCost}} +  \omega_{11} x_{j}^{\mathrm{accelTime}} +\\ &\omega_{12} x_{j}^{\mathrm{american}} +  \omega_{13} x_{j}^{\mathrm{japanese}} +  \omega_{14} x_{j}^{\mathrm{chinese}} +  \omega_{15} x_{j}^{\mathrm{skorean}} - p_{j}\\ &) +\varepsilon_{j} \end{split} \label{eq:mnlWtpCarsExample} \end{equation} ω\omega parameters units dollars λ\lambda scale parameter.

title: Estimating Mixed Logit Models
text: mixed logit model popular approach modeling unobserved heterogeneity across individuals, implemented assuming parameters vary randomly across individuals according chosen distribution (McFadden Train 2000). mixed logit model specified setting randPars argument logitr() function equal named vector defining parameter distributions. example , set randPars = c(feat = 'n', brand = 'n') feat brand normally distributed. current package version supports following distributions: Normal: "n" Log-normal: "ln" Zero-censored normal: "cn" Mixed logit models estimate mean standard deviation underlying normal distribution random coefficient. Note log-normal zero-censored normal parameters force positivity, using often necessary use negative value (e.g. “price”, typically negative coefficient). Mixed logit models logitr assume uncorrelated heterogeneity covariances default, though full covariances can estimated using correlation = TRUE argument. WTP space models, scalePar parameter can also modeled following random distribution setting randScale argument equal "n", "ln", "cn".

title: Estimating Mixed Logit Models
text: example uses yogurt data set Jain et al. (1994). data set contains 2,412 choice observations series yogurt purchases panel 100 households Springfield, Missouri, roughly two-year period. data collected optical scanners contain information price, brand, “feature” variable, identifies whether newspaper advertisement shown customer. four brands yogurt: Yoplait, Dannon, Weight Watchers, Hiland, market shares 34%, 40%, 23% 3%, respectively. utility models described , data variables represented follows:

title: Estimating Mixed Logit Models
text: example estimate following mixed logit model preference space: uj=αpj+β1xjFeat+β2xjHiland+β3xjWeight+β4xjYoplait+εj\begin{equation}     u_{j} =         \alpha p_{j} +         \beta_1 x_{j}^{\mathrm{Feat}} +         \beta_2 x_{j}^{\mathrm{Hiland}} +         \beta_3 x_{j}^{\mathrm{Weight}} +         \beta_4 x_{j}^{\mathrm{Yoplait}}  +         \varepsilon_{j} \label{eq:mnlPrefExample} \end{equation} parameters α\alpha, β1\beta_1, β2\beta_2, β3\beta_3, β4\beta_4 units utility. example , model β1\beta_1, β2\beta_2, β3\beta_3, β4\beta_4 normally distributed across population. result, model estimate mean standard deviation coefficients. Note since yogurt data panel structure (.e. multiple choice observations respondent), necessary set panelID argument id variable, identifies individual. use panel version log-likelihood (see Train 2009 chapter 6, section 6.7 details). Finally, WTP space models, recommended use multistart search mixed logit models non-convex. implemented example setting numMultiStarts = 10: Print summary results: summary table prints summaries estimated coefficients well summary table distribution 10,000 population draws normally-distributed model coefficient. results show feat attribute significant standard deviation coefficient, suggesting considerable heterogeneity across population attribute. contrast, brand coefficients small insignificant standard deviation coefficients. Compute WTP implied preference space model:

title: Estimating Mixed Logit Models
text: example estimate following mixed logit model WTP space: uj=λ(ω1xjFeat+ω2xjHiland+ω3xjWeight+ω4xjYoplait−pj)+εj\begin{equation}     u_{j} =         \lambda (         \omega_1 x_{j}^{\mathrm{Feat}} +         \omega_2 x_{j}^{\mathrm{Hiland}} +         \omega_3 x_{j}^{\mathrm{Weight}} +         \omega_4 x_{j}^{\mathrm{Yoplait}} -         p_{j})  +         \varepsilon_{j} \label{eq:mnlWtpExample} \end{equation} parameters ω1\omega_1, ω2\omega_2, ω3\omega_3, ω4\omega_4 units dollars λ\lambda scale parameter. example , model ω1\omega_1, ω2\omega_2, ω3\omega_3, ω4\omega_4 normally distributed across population. Note slightly different assumption preference space model. WTP space, assuming WTP features normally-distributed (opposed preference space model utility coefficients assumed follow normal distribution). example , also use 10-iteration multistart. also set starting values first iteration computed WTP preference space model: Print summary results: want compare WTP two different model spaces, use wtpCompare() function: Note WTP necessarily preference space WTP space MXL models. distributional assumptions MXL models imply different distributions WTP depending model space. See Train Weeks (2005) Sonnier, Ainslie, Otter (2007) details topic.
code: set.seed(6789)  mxl_wtp <- logitr(   data       = yogurt,   outcome    = 'choice',   obsID      = 'obsID',   panelID    = 'id',   pars       = c('feat', 'brand'),   scalePar   = 'price',   randPars   = c(feat = 'n', brand = 'n'),   numMultiStarts = 10,   startVals = wtp_mxl_pref$Estimate ) summary(mxl_wtp) #> ================================================= #>  #> Model estimated on: Wed Sep 27 08:37:40 2023  #>  #> Using logitr version: 1.1.1  #>  #> Call: #> logitr(data = yogurt, outcome = "choice", obsID = "obsID", pars = c("feat",  #>     "brand"), scalePar = "price", randPars = c(feat = "n", brand = "n"),  #>     panelID = "id", startVals = wtp_mxl_pref$Estimate, numMultiStarts = 10,  #>     numCores = numCores) #>  #> Frequencies of alternatives: #>        1        2        3        4  #> 0.402156 0.029436 0.229270 0.339138  #>  #> Summary Of Multistart Runs: #>    Log Likelihood Iterations Exit Status #> 1       -1239.294        110           3 #> 2       -1252.536         76           3 #> 3       -1258.974         87           3 #> 4       -1342.088        110           4 #> 5       -1250.922        111           3 #> 6       -1266.990         66           3 #> 7       -1268.352         81           3 #> 8       -1239.294         76           3 #> 9       -1258.974         60           3 #> 10      -1239.294         51           3 #>  #> Use statusCodes() to view the meaning of each status code #>  #> Exit Status: 3, Optimization stopped because ftol_rel or ftol_abs was reached. #>                                   #> Model Type:           Mixed Logit #> Model Space:   Willingness-to-Pay #> Model Run:                8 of 10 #> Iterations:                    76 #> Elapsed Time:            0h:0m:2s #> Algorithm:         NLOPT_LD_LBFGS #> Weights Used?:              FALSE #> Panel ID:                      id #> Robust? title: Estimating Mixed Logit Models

title: Predicting Probabilities and Outcomes with Estimated Models
text: example , preference space MNL model estimated (mnl_pref) used predict probabilities data used estimate model: predict() method returns data frame containing observation ID well predicted probabilities. original data can also returned data frame setting returnData = TRUE: make predictions new set alternatives, use newdata argument. example makes predictions just two choice observations yogurt dataset: Upper lower bounds confidence interval predicted probabilities can obtained setting interval = "confidence", tolerance level (0 1) set level argument (defaults 0.95). Intervals estimated using Krinsky Robb parametric bootstrapping method (Krinsky Robb 1986). example, 95% CI obtained following:

title: Predicting Probabilities and Outcomes with Estimated Models
text: WTP space models can also used predict probabilities. example , WTP space model estimated used predict probabilities data data frame previous examples: bar chart comparing predicted probabilities preference space WTP space models. Since models equivalent except different spaces, predicted probabilities identical:
code: mnl_wtp <- logitr(   data     = yogurt,   outcome  = 'choice',   obsID    = 'obsID',   pars     = c('feat', 'brand'),   scalePar = 'price',   numMultiStarts = 10 )  probs_mnl_wtp <- predict(   mnl_wtp,   newdata  = data,   obsID    = "obsID",   interval = "confidence" )  probs_mnl_wtp #>     obsID predicted_prob predicted_prob_lower predicted_prob_upper #> 49     13     0.43686141           0.41551327           0.45747039 #> 50     13     0.03312947           0.02641714           0.04231684 #> 51     13     0.19154829           0.17587927           0.20730602 #> 52     13     0.33846083           0.31857077           0.35854611 #> 165    42     0.60767120           0.57326014           0.63983775 #> 166    42     0.02601800           0.01853595           0.03664343 #> 167    42     0.17802364           0.16178241           0.19419803 #> 168    42     0.18828717           0.16779266           0.20839887 library("ggplot2")  probs <- rbind(probs_mnl_pref, probs_mnl_wtp) probs$model <- c(rep("mnl_pref", 8), rep("mnl_wtp", 8)) probs$alt <- rep(c("dannon", "hiland", "weight", "yoplait"), 4) probs$obs <- paste0("Observation ID: ", probs$obsID) ggplot(probs, aes(x = alt, y = predicted_prob, fill = model)) +     geom_bar(stat = 'identity', width = 0.7, position = "dodge") +     geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = predicted_prob_lower, ymax = predicted_prob_upper),                   width = 0.2, position = position_dodge(width = 0.7)) +     facet_wrap(vars(obs)) +     scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 1)) +     labs(x = 'Alternative', y = 'Expected Choice Probabilities') +     theme_bw()

title: Predicting Probabilities and Outcomes with Estimated Models
text: predict() method can also used predict outcomes setting type = "outcome" (default "prob" predicting probabilities). examples , outcomes predicted using preference space WTP space models previous examples. returnData argument also set TRUE predicted outcomes can compared actual choices made: accuracy model can computed dividing number correctly predicted choices total number choices: results show models correctly predicted choice approximately 39% observations yogurt data frame, significantly better random (25%).
code: outcomes_pref <- predict(     mnl_pref,      type = "outcome",      returnData = TRUE )  head(outcomes_pref) #>   obsID predicted_outcome price feat brandhiland brandweight brandyoplait #> 1     1                 0   8.1    0           0           0            0 #> 2     1                 0   6.1    0           1           0            0 #> 3     1                 1   7.9    0           0           1            0 #> 4     1                 0  10.8    0           0           0            1 #> 5     2                 1   9.8    0           0           0            0 #> 6     2                 0   6.4    0           1           0            0 #>   choice #> 1      0 #> 2      0 #> 3      1 #> 4      0 #> 5      1 #> 6      0  outcomes_wtp <- predict(     mnl_wtp,      type = "outcome",      returnData = TRUE )  head(outcomes_wtp) #>   obsID predicted_outcome feat brandhiland brandweight brandyoplait scalePar #> 1     1                 1    0           0           0            0      8.1 #> 2     1                 0    0           1           0            0      6.1 #> 3     1                 0    0           0           1            0      7.9 #> 4     1                 0    0           0           0            1     10.8 #> 5     2                 1    0           0           0            0      9.8 #> 6     2                 0    0           1           0            0      6.4 #>   choice #> 1      0 #> 2      0 #> 3      1 #> 4      0 #> 5      1 #> 6      0 chosen_pref <- subset(outcomes_pref, choice == 1) chosen_pref$correct <- chosen_pref$choice == chosen_pref$predicted_outcome accuracy_pref <- sum(chosen_pref$correct) / nrow(chosen_pref) accuracy_pref #> [1] 0.3909619  chosen_wtp <- subset(outcomes_wtp, choice == 1) chosen_wtp$correct <- chosen_wtp$choice == chosen_wtp$predicted_outcome accuracy_wtp <- sum(chosen_wtp$correct) / nrow(chosen_wtp) accuracy_wtp #> [1] 0.356136

title: Summarizing Results
text: Often times need create summary tables formatted publication. {gtsummary} package offers convenient solution works well logitrmodels. example, formatted summary table can obtained using tbl_regression() function: tbl_regression() function many options customizing output table. example, can change coefficient names label argument: {gtsummary} package supports wide variety output types, including support LaTeX. One create table tbl_regression(), can print variety ways. example, ’ve created table x, can print LaTeX following ways: as_gt(x) |> gt::as_latex() as_kable_extra(x, format = "latex") as_hux_table(x) |> to_latex() as_kable(x, format = "latex") Multiple models can also printed table:
code: library(gtsummary)  model |>    tbl_regression() model |>    tbl_regression(     label = list(         feat = "Newspaper ad shown?",         brand = "Yogurt's brand"     )   ) x <- model |>   tbl_regression() model1 <- model  model2 <- logitr(   data    = yogurt,   outcome = "choice",   obsID   = "obsID",   pars    = c("price*feat", "brand") )  # Make individual tables t1 <- tbl_regression(model1) t2 <- tbl_regression(model2)  # Merge tables tbl_merge(   tbls = list(t1, t2),   tab_spanner = c("**Baseline**", "**Interaction**") )

title: Summarizing Results

title: Utility Models in the Preference & WTP Space
text: random utility model well-established framework many fields estimating consumer preferences observed consumer choices (Louviere, Hensher, Swait 2000; Train 2009). Random utility models assume consumers choose alternative jj set alternatives greatest utility uju_{j}. Utility random variable modeled uj=vj+εju_{j} = v_{j} + \varepsilon_{j}, vjv_{j} “observed utility” (function observed attributes vj=f(𝐱j)v_{j} = f(\mathbf{x}_{j})) εj\varepsilon_{j} random variable representing portion utility unobservable modeler. Adopting notation Helveston et al. (2018), consider following utility model: uj*=𝛃*′𝐱j+α*pj+εj*,εj*∼Gumbel(0,σ2π26)\begin{equation}     u^*_{j} =         \boldsymbol{\beta}^{*'} \mathbf{x}_{j} +         \alpha^{*} p_{j} +         \varepsilon^{*}_{j},         \quad\quad         \varepsilon^{*}_{j} \sim \textrm{Gumbel}\left(0, \sigma^2\frac{\pi^2}{6}\right) \label{eq:utility} \end{equation} 𝛃*\boldsymbol{\beta}^{*} vector coefficients non-price attributes 𝐱j\mathbf{x}_{j}, α*\alpha^{*} coefficient price pjp_{j}, error term, εj*\varepsilon^{*}_{j}, IID random variable Gumbel extreme value distribution mean zero variance σ2(π2/6)\sigma^2(\pi^2/6). model identified since exists infinite set combinations values 𝛃*\boldsymbol{\beta}^{*}, α*\alpha^{*}, σ\sigma produce choice probabilities. order specify identifiable model, modeler must normalize equation . One approach normalize scale error term dividing equation σ\sigma, producing “preference space” utility specification: (uj*σ)=(𝛃*σ)′𝐱j+(α*σ)pj+(εj*σ),(εj*σ)∼Gumbel(0,π26)\begin{equation}     \left(\frac{u^*_{j}}{\sigma}\right) =         \left( \frac{\boldsymbol{\beta}^{*}}{\sigma} \right)' \mathbf{x}_{j} +         \left( \frac{\alpha^{*}}{\sigma} \right) p_{j} +         \left( \frac{\varepsilon^{*}_{j}}{\sigma} \right),         \quad\quad         \left( \frac{\varepsilon^{*}_{j}}{\sigma} \right) \sim \textrm{Gumbel}\left(0, \frac{\pi^2}{6}\right) \label{eq:utilityPreferenceScaled} \end{equation} typical preference space parameterization multinomial logit (MNL) model can written rewriting equation () uj=(uj*/σ)u_j = (u^*_j / \sigma), 𝛃=(𝛃*/σ)\boldsymbol{\beta}= (\boldsymbol{\beta}^{*} / \sigma), α=(α*/σ)\alpha = (\alpha^{*} / \sigma), εj=(εj*/σ)\varepsilon_{j} = (\varepsilon^{*}_{j} / \sigma): uj=𝛃′𝐱j+αpj+εj,εj∼Gumbel(0,π26)\begin{equation}     u_{j} =         \boldsymbol{\beta}' \mathbf{x}_{j} +         \alpha p_{j} +         \varepsilon_{j},         \quad\quad         \varepsilon_{j} \sim \textrm{Gumbel}\left(0,\frac{\pi^2}{6}\right) \label{eq:utilityPreference} \end{equation} vector 𝛃\boldsymbol{\beta} represents marginal utility changes non-price attribute, α\alpha represents marginal utility obtained price reductions. addition, coefficients 𝛃\boldsymbol{\beta} α\alpha measured units utility, relative rather absolute meaning. alternative normalization approach normalize equation () −α*- \alpha^* instead σ\sigma, producing “willingness--pay (WTP) space” utility specification: (uj*−α*)=(𝛃*−α*)′𝐱j+(α*−α*)pj+(εj*−α*),(εj*−α*)∼Gumbel(0,σ2(−α*)2π26)\begin{equation}     \left(\frac{u^*_{j}}{- \alpha^*}\right) =         \left(\frac{\boldsymbol{\beta}^{*}}{- \alpha^{*}}\right)' \mathbf{x}_{j} +         \left(\frac{\alpha^{*}}{- \alpha^{*}}\right) p_{j} +         \left(\frac{\varepsilon^{*}_{j}}{- \alpha^{*}}\right),         \quad\quad         \left(\frac{\varepsilon^{*}_{j}}{- \alpha^{*}}\right) \sim \textrm{Gumbel} \left(0, \frac{\sigma^2}{(- \alpha^{*})^2}\frac{\pi^2}{6} \right) \label{eq:utilityWtpScaled} \end{equation} Since error term equation scaled λ2=σ2/(−α*)2\lambda^2 = \sigma^2/(- \alpha^{*})^2, can rewrite equation () multiplying what: Random utility logit models with preference and willingness to pay space parameterizations
title: Random utility logit models with preference and willingness to pay space parameterizations
text: logitr: Fast Estimation Multinomial (MNL) Mixed Logit (MXL) Models Preference Space Willingness Pay Space Utility Parameterizations latest version includes support : Multinomial logit (MNL) models Mixed logit (MXL) models normal log-normal parameter distributions. Preference space WTP space utility parameterizations. Weighted models differentially weight individual observations. Uncorrelated correlated heterogeneity covariances mixed logit models. Functions computing WTP preference space models. Functions predicting expected probabilities outcomes sets alternatives based estimated model. parallelized multistart optimization loop uses different random starting points iteration search different local minima (useful non-convex problems like MXL models models WTP space parameterizations). Mixed logit models estimated using maximum simulated likelihood based algorithms Kenneth Train’s book Discrete Choice Methods Simulation, 2nd Edition (New York: Cambridge University Press, 2009).

code: library(logitr)  # Estimate a preference space model mnl_pref <- logitr(   data    = yogurt,   outcome = "choice",   obsID   = "obsID",   pars    = c("price", "feat", "brand") ) #> Running model... #> Done!  # Obtain 10,000 draws of parameters from model coefs <- coef(mnl_pref) covariance <- vcov(mnl_pref) coef_draws <- as.data.frame(MASS::mvrnorm(10^4, coefs, covariance))  # Compute a confidence interval ci(coef_draws, level = 0.95) #>                    mean      lower      upper #> price        -0.3667998 -0.4132753 -0.3201336 #> feat          0.4895380  0.2535630  0.7233272 #> brandhiland  -3.7151127 -3.9958466 -3.4308442 #> brandweight  -0.6414189 -0.7465211 -0.5361054 #> brandyoplait  0.7355918  0.5771616  0.8900335

code: library(logitr)  # Estimate a preference space model mnl_pref <- logitr(   data    = yogurt,   outcome = "choice",   obsID   = "obsID",   pars    = c("price", "feat", "brand") ) #> Running model... #> Done!  # Create a set of alternatives for which to simulate probabilities # (Columns are attributes, rows are alternatives) data <- data.frame(   altID       = c(1, 2, 3, 4),   obsID       = c(1, 1, 1, 1),   price       = c(8, 6, 7, 10),   feat    = c(0, 1, 0, 0),   brand   = c('dannon', 'hiland', 'weight', 'yoplait') )  # Obtain 10,000 draws of parameters from model coefs <- coef(mnl_pref) covariance <- vcov(mnl_pref) coef_draws <- as.data.frame(MASS::mvrnorm(10^4, coefs, covariance))  # Compute the probabilities sim <- logit_probs(   mnl_pref,   coef_draws = coef_draws,   newdata = data,   obsID = 'obsID',   level = 0.95 )

text: data data, formatted data.frame object. outcome name column identifies outcome variable, coded 1 TRUE 0 FALSE. obsID name column identifies observation. pars names parameters estimated model. Must column names data argument. WTP space models, include scalePar variable pars. scalePar name column identifies scale variable, typically "price" WTP space models, continuous variable, "time". Defaults NULL. randPars named vector whose names random parameters values distribution: 'n' normal, 'ln' log-normal, 'cn' zero-censored normal. Defaults NULL. randScale random distribution scale parameter: 'n' normal, 'ln' log-normal, 'cn' zero-censored normal. used WTP space MXL models. Defaults NULL. modelSpace argument longer needed v0.7.0. model space now determined based scalePar argument: NULL (default), model preference space, otherwise WTP space. Defaults NULL. weights name column identifies weights used model estimation. Defaults NULL. panelID name column identifies individual (panel data multiple observations recorded individual). Defaults NULL. clusterID name column identifies cluster groups used model estimation. Defaults NULL. robust Determines whether robust covariance matrix estimated. Defaults FALSE. Specification clusterID weights override user setting set `TRUE' (warning displayed case). Replicates functionality Stata's cmcmmixlogit. correlation Set TRUE account correlation across random parameters (correlated heterogeneity). Defaults FALSE. startValBounds sets lower upper bounds starting parameter values optimization run, generated runif(n, lower, upper). Defaults c(-1, 1). startVals vector values used starting values optimization. used first run numMultiStarts > 1. Defaults NULL. numMultiStarts number times run optimization loop, time starting different random starting point parameter startValBounds. Recommended non-convex models, WTP space models mixed logit models. Defaults 1. useAnalyticGrad Set FALSE use numerically approximated gradients instead analytic gradients estimation. now, using analytic gradient faster MNL models slower MXL models. Defaults TRUE. scaleInputs default variable data scaled 0 1 running optimization routine usually helps stability, especially variables large small values (e.g. > 10^3 < 10^-3). Set FALSE turn feature . Defaults TRUE. standardDraws default, new set standard normal draws generated call logitr (draws used multistart iteration). user can override draws providing matrix standard normal draws desired. Defaults NULL. drawType Specify draw type character: "halton" (default) "sobol" (recommended models 5 random parameters). numDraws number Halton draws use MXL models maximum simulated likelihood. Defaults 50. numCores number cores use parallel processing multistart. Set 1 serially run multistart. Defaults NULL, case number cores set parallel::detectCores() - 1. Max cores allowed capped parallel::detectCores(). vcov Set TRUE evaluate include variance-covariance matrix coefficient standard errors returned object. Defaults FALSE. predict FALSE, predicted probabilities, fitted values, residuals included returned object. Defaults TRUE. options list options controlling nloptr() optimization. code: # S3 method for class 'logitr' predict(   object,   newdata = NULL,   obsID = NULL,   type = "prob",   returnData = FALSE,   interval = "none",   level = 0.95,   numDrawsCI = 10^4,   pars = NULL,   scalePar = NULL,   randPars = NULL,   randScale = NULL,   ci,   ... )

title: Predict probabilities and / or outcomes — predict.logitr
text: object object class logitr (model estimated using 'logitr()` function). newdata data.frame. row alternative column attribute corresponding parameter names estimated model. Defaults NULL, case predictions made original data used estimate model. obsID name column identifies set alternatives data. Required newdata != NULL. Defaults NULL, case value obsID data object used. type character vector defining predict: prob probabilities, outcomes outcomes. want outputs, use c("prob", "outcome"). Outcomes predicted randomly according predicted probabilities. Defaults "prob". returnData TRUE data also returned, otherwise predicted values ("prob" /  "outcome") returned. Defaults FALSE. interval Type interval calculation: "none" (default) "confidence". Future versions include "prediction" intervals well. level Tolerance / confidence interval. Defaults 0.95. numDrawsCI number draws use simulating uncertainty computed CI. Defaults 10^4. pars names parameters estimated model. Must column names data argument. WTP space models, include scalePar variable pars. scalePar name column identifies scale variable, typically "price" WTP space models, continuous variable, "time". Defaults NULL. randPars named vector whose names random parameters values distribution: 'n' normal, 'ln' log-normal, 'cn' zero-censored normal. Defaults NULL. randScale random distribution scale parameter: 'n' normal, 'ln' log-normal, 'cn' zero-censored normal. used WTP space MXL models. Defaults NULL. ci longer used v1.1.0 - provided, passed level argument, interval set "confidence", warning displayed. ... arguments.

title: Predict probabilities and / or outcomes — predict.logitr
text: data frame predicted probabilities / outcomes.

title: Predict probabilities and / or outcomes — predict.logitr
code: library(logitr)  # Estimate a preference space model mnl_pref <- logitr(   data    = yogurt,   outcome = "choice",   obsID   = "obsID",   pars    = c("price", "feat", "brand") ) #> Running model... #> Done!  # Predict probabilities and / or outcomes  # Predict probabilities for each alternative in the model data probs <- predict(mnl_pref) head(probs) #>   obsID predicted_prob #> 1     1     0.41802407 #> 2     1     0.02118240 #> 3     1     0.23691737 #> 4     1     0.32387615 #> 5     2     0.26643822 #> 6     2     0.02255486  # Create a set of alternatives for which to make predictions. # Each row is an alternative and each column an attribute. data <- subset(     yogurt, obsID %in% c(42, 13),     select = c('obsID', 'alt', 'price', 'feat', 'brand')) data #> # A tibble: 8 × 5 #>   obsID   alt price  feat brand   #>   <int> <int> <dbl> <dbl> <chr>   #> 1    13     1  8.1      0 dannon  #> 2    13     2  5.00     0 hiland  #> 3    13     3  8.60     0 weight  #> 4    13     4 10.8      0 yoplait #> 5    42     1  6.30     0 dannon  #> 6    42     2  6.10     1 hiland  #> 7    42     3  7.90     0 weight  #> 8    42     4 11.5      0 yoplait  # Predict probabilities using the estimated model predict(mnl_pref, newdata = data, obsID = "obsID") #>   obsID predicted_prob #> 1    13     0.43685145 #> 2    13     0.03312986 #> 3    13     0.19155548 #> 4    13     0.33846321 #> 5    42     0.60764778 #> 6    42     0.02602007 #> 7    42     0.17803313 #> 8    42     0.18829902  # Predict probabilities and include a 95% confidence interval predict(   mnl_pref,   newdata = data,   obsID = "obsID",   interval = "confidence",   level = 0.95 ) #>   obsID predicted_prob predicted_prob_lower predicted_prob_upper #> 1    13     0.43685145           0.41614493           0.45781416 #> 2    13     0.03312986           0.02627197           0.04176048 #> 3    13     0.19155548           0.17623321           0.20826852 #> 4    13     0.33846321           0.31881357           0.35845900 #> 5    42     0.60764778           0.57396714           0.63975396 #> 6    42     0.02602007           0.01828488           0.03671086 #> 7    42     0.17803313           0.16225859           0.19513148 #> 8    42     0.18829902           0.16834918           0.20914257  # Predict outcomes predict(mnl_pref, newdata = data, obsID = "obsID", type = "outcome") #>   obsID predicted_outcome #> 1    13                 1 #> 2    13                 0 #> 3    13                 0 #> 4    13                 0 #> 5    42                 0 #> 6    42                 0 #> 7    42                 0 #> 8    42                 1  # Predict outcomes and probabilities predict(mnl_pref, newdata = data, obsID = "obsID", type = c("prob", "outcome")) #>   obsID predicted_prob predicted_outcome #> 1    13     0.43685145                 0 #> 2    13     0.03312986                 0 #> 3    13     0.19155548                 1 #> 4    13     0.33846321                 0 #> 5    42     0.60764778                 1 #> 6    42     0.02602007                 0 #> 7    42     0.17803313                 0 #> 8    42     0.18829902                 0

title: View a description the nloptr status codes — statusCodes
code: statusCodes() #> Status codes: #> 1: Generic success return value. #> 2: Optimization stopped because stopval was reached. #> 3: Optimization stopped because ftol_rel or ftol_abs was reached. #> 4: Optimization stopped because xtol_rel or xtol_abs was reached. #> 5: Optimization stopped because maxeval was reached. #> 6: Optimization stopped because maxtime was reached. #> -1: Generic failure code. #> -2: Invalid arguments (e.g. lower bounds are bigger than upper bounds, an unknown algorithm was specified, etc.). #> -3: Ran out of memory. #> -4: Halted because roundoff errors limited progress. (In this case, the optimization still typically returns a useful result.) #> -5: Halted because of a forced termination: the user called nlopt_force_stop(opt) on the optimization's nlopt_opt object opt from the user's objective function or constraints.

title: Compare WTP from preference and WTP space models — wtpCompare
code: library(logitr)  # Estimate a MNL model in the Preference space mnl_pref <- logitr(   data    = yogurt,   outcome = "choice",   obsID   = "obsID",   pars    = c("price", "feat", "brand") ) #> Running model... #> Done!  # Compute the WTP implied from the preference space model wtp_mnl_pref <- wtp(mnl_pref, scalePar = "price")  # Estimate a MNL model in the WTP Space, using the computed WTP values # from the preference space model as starting points mnl_wtp <- logitr(   data      = yogurt,   outcome   = "choice",   obsID     = "obsID",   pars      = c("feat", "brand"),   scalePar  = "price",   startVals = wtp_mnl_pref$Estimate ) #> Running model... #> Done!  # Compare the WTP between the two spaces wtpCompare(mnl_pref, mnl_wtp, scalePar = "price") #>                       pref           wtp  difference #> scalePar         0.3665546     0.3665214 -0.00003318 #> feat             1.3406987     1.3414660  0.00076735 #> brandhiland    -10.1362190   -10.1370357 -0.00081666 #> brandweight     -1.7490940    -1.7499898 -0.00089581 #> brandyoplait     2.0038476     2.0038255 -0.00002216 #> logLik       -2656.8878790 -2656.8878960 -0.00001696
